$interpreted:
Beyata: It’s fine, really... You know Yao has a temper.
He said he won’t harm you, so he won’t.
Worried Girl: Well, if you’re sure, bluebird...
Worried Girl: ...Yes, this is mine.
Pang: Then you and that artisan—
Worried Girl: ...If it’s gotten this far, I guess there's no use hiding it.

Worried Girl: The two of us are just close friends, there’s nothing else between us.
It’s just nice to have someone else to talk to...
Worried Girl: A couple of days ago he came to see me, told me he had to leave Hot Spring Street.
Worried Girl: He asked if I knew a back road out of town, one where he could leave unnoticed.
Yao: And did you know of one?

Worried Girl: Of course. It’s my job to listen, to know things.
I told him about it, a small road...
Worried Girl: Anyway, that’s as much as I know.
Beyata: Is that enough, Yao?
Yao: It's enough.
Worried Girl: Wait!

Worried Girl: I... I saw the look in his eyes...
I could tell he’d gotten himself into some kind of trouble.

Worried Girl: I didn’t dare ask him what he’d done,
and I know I can’t ask you to go easy on him...
Yao: ...But you do wish something of me?
Worried Girl: No matter what you end up doing to him, please don’t say it was me who sold him out.
Worried Girl: I... I mean a lot to him... please!
Yao: ...You have my word.
Worried Girl: Thank you! Thank you so much!
Pang: This must be the road she was talking about. It definitely looks pretty rough... I wonder how far the artisan could have gotten by now.
Yao: ...You should head back. I can do this on my own.
Pang: No, I have business with the artisan, too.
Yao: What business?
Pang: ...That diplomat said, if I give him details on the artisan then he’ll help me win the tournament.
Yao: Huh? You’re looking for the artisan so you can cheat?
Yao: I always pegged you as the honorable type... I guess you've cha—
Pang: It’s not for me. It’s for the insect princess...
Yao: Insect princess?
Pang: I couldn’t help her save her people... but I can help her win the tournament, and stay alive!
Yao: ...You’re looking for the artisan so you can help someone else?
Pang: That’s right. I don’t want things to be like they were back then...
Yao: Ah... hah! Hahahahah!
Yao: I thought after all these years you might have changed, but no! You're still the same old hypocrite!
Pang: Excuse me!?
Yao: That's right.
Yao: Just like all those years ago, prattling on and on about justice! And stabbing me in the back all the while!
Artisan: D-Don't eat me! Somebody, help!!
Pang: Hagh... agh...
Yao: Heh... Been a while since we’ve done that.
Pang: Damn, must have smelled the blood!
Yao: Run!
Artisan: I-I can’t, I think I’m in shock!
Pang: Get him out of here, I’ll distract them!
Yao: But you...

Pang: Come on, Yao.
You of all people should know I can handle it!
Yao: ...Hmph, fine.
Artisan: Mngh... Ow! That hurts!
Artisan: What are you doing!?
Yao: What am I doing?
Yao: —Seeing how long it'll take before you talk!
Artisan: I-I don’t know what you’re talking about! Your friend back there...
Yao: I’d worry about yourself right now, not him.
Yao: What other orders have you taken lately, other than mine? Why is the Kingdom of the Sun looking for you!?
Artisan: I... I can’t say...
Artisan: It doesn’t matter how much you beat me, I’ll never tell!
Yao: We'll just see about that.
Artisan: Y-You’re crazy! Somebody, help!!
Artisan: ...Stop, please! Stop hitting me!
Artisan: Just stop, I don’t know anything! I swear!
Artisan: Fine, I’ll talk! Just stop!!

Yao: Do you have records of everything?
Where are they?
Artisan: *Cough*... I was afraid... they’d find them... so I... *cough* I put the records together with your order, and I hid it all...
Artisan: If you let go of me, I’ll take you to it. *cough*
Pang: Yao? Yao!
Yao: You’re back.
Pang: Yes... What about you two? Were you chased by more beasts?
Yao: Nothing I couldn't handle.
Yao: But he had quite the scare, passed out on the road.
Pang: Really...
Pang: What? Sizing me up?
Yao: ...No, I just... thought of something.
Yao: Just thinking about the past, the time we went exploring in the forest that one night.
Pang: You mean the time we didn’t come back until dawn, covered in bruises?
Pang: How could I forget. I got an earful from the chieftain...
Yao: You warned me not to go, but then ended up coming along. At that point I knew... you probably loved breaking the rules even more than I did.
Pang: ...What nonsense...
Yao: Yep... Everything's always been just a bunch of nonsense.
Pang: Yao... all those years ago—
Yao: Forget about it. You should get going.
Pang: Ah, you’re right. I have to bring this artisan to that diplomat.
Pang: Wait, your leg!
Yao: ...Just a scrape. Nothing to worry about.
Pang: What do you mean a scrape? I know how fierce those beasts are!
Yao: Hmph... I’m still alive, aren’t I?
Pang: Stop it, Yao! I should take you to the doctor!
Yao: What doctor? You think I can just show my face to any random doctor?
Yao: ...It doesn’t matter. Just deal with the artisan.
Pang: Then just wait here, I’ll bring back some medicine.
Yao: You’re wasting your time...
Pang: Just hold on. I’ll be as quick as I can.
Yao: ...Show yourself.
Dracontine: Your wound...
Yao: I’m fine, it was just an excuse to buy some time.
Yao: Now... can you find something for me?
Dracontine: No offense, but you are not my master.
Yao: I know that, of course—
Yao: But I know you’ve been ordered to assist me, for the good of us all.
Dracontine: Yes, but...
Yao: Relax, I wouldn’t ask if it didn't benefit the plan.
Yao: Do this one thing for me, and maybe I’ll forget the fact that you’ve been stalking me on your own accord. Otherwise...
Dracontine: ...Fine. What is it you’re looking for?

Yao: Apart from... there are still some more...
They're located at...
Pang: Whew... Yao? Sorry I took so long...
Pang: He’s still breathing...
Pang: But... where's Yao!?
